revision.text:
{{refimprove|date=September 2010}}
An '''abortive flower'''<ref>{{cite journal | last=Smith | first=Arma A. | title=Abortive Flower Buds of Trillium | journal=Botanical Gazette | year=1896 | jstor=2464003 | volume=22 | issue=5 | pages=402–403 | issn=0006-8071 | doi=10.1086/327429}}</ref> is a [[flower]] that has a [[stamen]] but an under developed, or no [[pistil]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://webstersdictionary1828.com/Dictionary/abortive|title=Websters Dictionary 1828 - Webster's Dictionary 1828 - abortive|website=Websters Dictionary 1828|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref> It falls without producing fruit or seeds, due to its inability to [[wikt:fructify|fructify]]. Flowers require both male and female organs to reproduce, and the pistils and ovary serve as female organs, while the stamens are considered male organs.
Illustrative examples include ''[[Urginea Nagarjunae|Urginea nagarjunae]]'' and ''[[Trichilogaster acaciaelongifoliae]]''.
==== Causes of Flower Abortion ==== Pollinated flowers and fruits can abort selectively. It could be because of the order of pollination, the number of developing seeds, pollen source, or some combination of these.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stephenson|first=A G|date=1981|title=Flower and Fruit Abortion: Proximate Causes and Ultimate Functions|url=https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/10.1146/annurev.es.12.110181.001345|journal=Annual Review of Ecology and Systematics|language=en|volume=12|issue=1|pages=253–279|doi=10.1146/annurev.es.12.110181.001345|issn=0066-4162|via=}}</ref> Flowers and fruits can also abort because of outside causes like insufficient light, unsuitable photo-period, high temperature, nutrient deficiency, [[ethylene]], [[Drought tolerance|drought stress]]. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gpnmag.com/article/causes-of-flower-bud-abortion/|title=Causes of Flower Bud Abortion - Greenhouse Product News|work=Greenhouse Product News|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en-US}}</ref>
There is research to suggest that random selective abortions based on the timing of fertilization could increase the genetic quality of seeds.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ezoe|first=Hideo|date=2018-06-09|title=Excessive flower production as an anti-predator strategy: when is random flower abortion favored?|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs10144-018-0625-6|journal=Population Ecology|language=en|volume=60|issue=3|pages=275–286|doi=10.1007/s10144-018-0625-6|issn=1438-3896}}</ref> The age of the flower also has an effect on the percentage of abortion. The older the flower, the more likely it is to be aborting the fruit or pollen.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ferguson|first=Nesta|date=1924|title=On The Determination of the Percentage of Abortive Pollen in Plants|url=http://jeb.biologists.org/content/2/1/65|journal=Journal of Experimental Biology|volume=2|pages=65-73|via=The Company of Biologists Ltd}}</ref>
